am_hard_4 = {
    "id": 2139, "role": "am", "category": "technical", "difficulty": "hard",
    "title": "Currency Overlay and Hedging in International Equity Portfolios",
    "question": "How do you design a currency hedging program for an international equity portfolio? Discuss the trade-off between hedging costs, volatility reduction, carry dynamics, and when it makes sense to leave currency exposure unhedged. How do dynamic hedging strategies with rolling forwards and options work?",
    "modelAnswer": "Currency hedging in international portfolios aims to reduce the volatility contribution of FX to total portfolio returns.\n\n**Currency Exposure in International Portfolios:**\nA US investor holding European equities: Total return = Euro stock return (%) + FX return (EUR/USD). Equity vol 15-20%, FX vol 10-12%. Correlation between equity and FX varies: when EUR weakens, Euro stocks may also fall (export-oriented stocks) or rise (domestic stocks) -> hedging reduces vol but may have expected cost.\n\n**Hedging Decision Framework:**\n1. Hedging reduces volatility of international equity returns by 30-50%.\n2. Hedging cost = interest rate differential (forward points). If EUR/USD forward points negative (EUR rates lower than USD), hedger receives premium -> hedging has positive carry. If EUR rates higher, hedging costs money.\n3. UIP puzzle: Forward premium does not predict currency returns well. Rolling hedges at forward rates can have positive or negative impact vs unhedged.\n\n**Standard Approach: 50% Hedged (Institutional Norm):**\nMany institutional portfolios hedge 50% of currency exposure. Balances vol reduction with cost. Past performance: 50% hedged MSCI EAFE has 12-13% vol vs 16-17% for unhedged, vs 14-15% for fully hedged.\n\n**Full vs Partial Hedging:**\n- Full hedging: Hedge all currency exposure. Pro: Minimizes vol. Con: Removes all currency alpha. May be costly if base currency strengthens.\n- Dynamic hedging: Adjust hedge ratio based on valuation (PPP, real rates), momentum (trend-following), or carry differential.\n\n**Implementation:**\n- Rolling forwards: Monthly or quarterly roll. Sell EUR 3M forward, let expire, sell new forward. Cost = EUR/USD basis.\n- Options: Buy put options on EUR/USD for downside protection (floor). Premium cost 1-3% per year depending on strike. Can be funded by selling OTM calls (collar structure).\n- Non-deliverable forwards (NDFs): For emerging market currencies with capital controls.\n\n**Dynamic Hedging Strategies:**\n1. PPP-based: Hedge when currency is overvalued vs PPP (e.g., EUR/USD > 1.30 for EUR). Unhedge when undervalued.\n2. Carry-based: Hedge high-yield currencies (long hedges that earn positive carry). Unhedge low-yield currencies (short hedges that cost).\n3. Momentum-based: Increase hedge ratio when base currency is strengthening (trend. Decrease when weakening.\n4. Volatility-adjusted: Higher hedge ratio when FX vol > equity vol (hedging more valuable).\n\n**Forward Roll Mechanics:**\n- For a hedger with $100M EUR portfolio at 50% hedge ratio:\n  1. Sell EUR 50M 1-month forward at 1.10.\n  2. At expiry, portfolio EUR exposure is X, FX gain/loss = (X - 50M) x (actual spot - 1.10).\n  3. Roll: Close expired forward, enter new 1-month forward at current rate.\n  4. Net result: Hedge ratio returns to 50% after rebalancing.\n\n**Hedging Costs Over Time:**\n- Eurozone investor hedging USD: 10-year average cost ~1.5% per year (USD rates > EUR rates, paying forward points).\n- US investor hedging EUR: 10-year average cost ~0.5% (EUR rates lower than USD).\n- Emerging markets: Hedging cost can be 3-8% per year (high local rates but depreciation offsets carry).\n\n**When Not to Hedge:**\n- Strategic view that USD will weaken (long-term dollar bear theme).\n- Portfolio already has natural hedges (USD revenues, USD liabilities).\n- Illiquid currencies (no deep forward market).\n- Small FX exposure (<5% of portfolio).\n\n**Risk Considerations:**\n- Basis risk: If FX exposure (from equities) and hedge notional don't match (equity value changes). Need dynamic rebalancing.\n- Counterparty risk: Forward contracts are OTC - ISDA/master agreement required.\n- Liquidity: G10 currencies deep, EM currencies less so.\n\n**Example:** $500M global equity portfolio (60% US, 30% Europe, 10% Japan). Hedge 50% of EUR and JPY exposures.\n- EUR exposure: $150M. 50% hedge = $75M EUR/USD forward sell.\n- JPY exposure: $50M. 50% hedge = $25M USD/JPY forward buy (selling JPY).\n- Net carry: EUR/USD forward (EUR rates 3.0%, USD 4.5%) = 1.5% annual gain. JPY/USD (JPY 0.5%, USD 4.5%) = 4% annual gain.\n- Total carry from hedging: 0.30 x 0.5 x 1.5% + 0.10 x 0.5 x 4% = 0.225% + 0.2% = +0.425% annual.\n\n**Interview Tip:** Show understanding that hedging is a risk management tool, not a return generator. Know the difference between forward cost (carry) and option-based hedging (premium). The 50% hedge question is a standard institutional interview topic.",
    "scoringKeywords": {"hedge ratio 50% institutional norm": 15, "forward rolling mechanics carry cost": 15, "PPP momentum dynamic hedging": 15, "options collar structure": 10, "volatility reduction 30-50%": 15, "UIP puzzle hedging decision": 10, "basis risk equity value changes": 10, "emerging market NDFs illiquidity": 10},
    "expectedStructure": ["Currency exposure in international portfolios", "Hedging decision framework and vol reduction", "Dynamic hedging strategies", "Implementation mechanics (forwards, options)", "When not to hedge and portfolio construction"],
    "entryLevel": False, "stars": 5
}

am_hard_5 = {
    "id": 2140, "role": "am", "category": "technical", "difficulty": "hard",
    "title": "Illiquid Assets in Institutional Portfolios: Pricing, Rebalancing, and Performance",
    "question": "How do institutional investors incorporate illiquid assets (private equity, real estate, infrastructure, private credit) into multi-asset portfolios? Discuss the challenges of pricing unobservable assets, portfolio rebalancing with lock-ups, and the denominator effect during market stress.",
    "modelAnswer": "Illiquid assets offer a liquidity premium (typically 200-500 bps over public equivalents) but introduce valuation uncertainty and rebalancing challenges.\n\n**Allocation Framework:**\nTypical institutional allocation: 10-30% of portfolio in illiquid assets (pension funds 20-30%, endowments 15-25%, insurance 10-15%).\n- Private equity: 8-12% target\n- Private credit: 5-8%\n- Real estate: 5-10%\n- Infrastructure: 3-8%\n- Natural resources: 2-5%\n\n**Liquidity Premium (LP):**\n- Illiquid assets earn excess returns: LP = 200-500 bps over comparable public market equivalents (PMEs).\n- But part of LP is illiquidity risk premium, part is leverage, part is stale pricing (smoothing).\n- Stale pricing: Private assets are marked quarterly (or annually) with smoothed valuations. This understates true risk (vol is artificially low).\n\n**Pricing Challenges:**\n1. Valuation lag: PE/RE funds report NAV with 1-3 quarter lag. Current market value unknown. Creates 'stale beta' issue.\n2. Appraisal smoothing: Valuations by third-party appraisers use past transactions, not current market. Creates autocorrelation in returns (0.4-0.7). True vol may be 2-3x reported vol.\n3. Geltner method: De-smooth returns: r_true(t) = (r_observed(t) - alpha x r_observed(t-1)) / (1 - alpha), where alpha is smoothing coefficient. Typical alpha for RE = 0.4-0.6.\n4. PME (Public Market Equivalent): Compare PE returns to public index with same cash flow timing.\n\n**J-Curve in Private Equity:**\n- Early years: Negative returns (management fees, deal costs, write-offs).\n- Years 3-5: Returns turn positive as investments mature.\n- Years 5-10: Harvest period with distributions.\n- Impact on portfolio: Commitment-based, not investment-based. Fund must have cash available for capital calls (typically 20-30% of commitment in first 2 years).\n\n**Denominator Effect:**\nDuring market downturns (2008, 2020, 2022):\n- Public portfolio value falls -> illiquid allocation % increases (denominator shrinks, numerator stays same).\n- Example: 20% PE allocation, public markets fall 30%. If PE NAV unchanged: allocation jumps to 20/(80x0.7+20) = 26%. Above target -> need to sell.\n- But illiquid assets are hard to sell. Solution: Reduce pace of new commitments, use secondaries market, or wait for rebalancing via distributions.\n- In 2008, many institutional investors breached allocation limits (California pensions went from 8% to 14% PE).\n\n**Portfolio Construction with Illiquids:**\n1. Commitment pacing model: New commitments = Target allocation x (Desired Pace x Expected Distributions). Smooth capital calls over 3-5 years.\n2. Over-commitment strategy: Since not all committed capital is called immediately, commit 120-130% of target to maintain effective exposure.\n3. Cash flow forecasting: Model expected capital calls (20-30% in year 1, 40-50% in years 2-3) and distributions (start year 3-5, continue through fund life).\n4. Liquidity buffer: Hold 5-10% in cash/short-term bonds for capital calls.\n\n**Risk Metrics:**\n- Modified Sharpe: Use de-smoothed vol for ratio calculation.\n- Liquidity-at-Risk (LaR): Maximum expected cash outflow from capital calls over 3-12 months at 95% confidence.\n- Liquidity coverage: Available cash + undrawn credit lines / Expected capital calls over 12 months.\n\n**Modern Approaches:**\n- Liquid alternatives: Use liquid alt funds (daily liquidity) to gain illiquid exposure via replication.\n- Co-investment: Direct deals alongside PE funds (reduces fee drag, better illiquidity premium capture).\n- Secondaries: Buy/sell PE fund stakes in secondary market. Offers liquidity exit at 5-20% discount to NAV.\n- Hybrid structures: Evergreen funds (semi-liquid, quarterly redemption with gates).\n\n**Real-World:** Yale Endowment (David Swensen model): 30% PE, 15% RE, 10% Natural Resources. Only 5% cash for rebalancing. Relies on distribution yield and new commitments for inflow. Endowment outperformed by 2-3% annually with higher illiquidity allocation.\n\n**Interview Tip:** Emphasize understanding that illiquid asset risk is often understated by standard deviation. Use the denominator effect to demonstrate practical knowledge of rebalancing challenges during crises. The Geltner de-smoothing method and PME are advanced topics to mention.",
    "scoringKeywords": {"liquidity premium 200-500 bps stale pricing": 15, "appraisal smoothing Geltner de-smoothing": 10, "denominator effect 2008 2022 rebalancing": 20, "commitment pacing over-commitment": 15, "J-curve private equity cash flows": 10, "PME public market equivalent comparison": 10, "secondaries liquidity at discount": 10, "Yale endowment Swensen model": 10},
    "expectedStructure": ["Institutional allocation to illiquid assets", "Pricing and valuation challenges", "Denominator effect and rebalancing", "Commitment pacing and cash flow modeling", "Modern approaches and risk management"],
    "entryLevel": False, "stars": 5
}

